PM Frontend Design Skill
This skill guides creation of distinctive, production-grade project management
interfaces. PM tools are among the most visually homogenized software
categories — Linear, Notion, Jira, Asana, Monday all blend together. The goal
is to escape that gravitational pull while remaining genuinely usable by real
teams. This is not a portfolio toy; it must be functional AND unforgettable.

Implement real, working code with exceptional attention to aesthetic detail,
information hierarchy, and interaction quality.

Phase 1 — Domain Understanding
Before any code, understand the PM context deeply:

Scope: What is being built? (Single component? Full dashboard? Onboarding
flow? Data-dense list? Empty state?)
Data model: What entities are in play? (Projects, tasks, sprints, epics,
users, milestones, blockers, labels, priorities?)
User role: Who is looking at this? (IC contributor, team lead, exec
stakeholder, external client?) The information hierarchy must serve them.
Workflow moment: What is the user trying to do right now? Create
something? Triage? Review progress? Find a blocker? Design for the action,
not the entity.
Team size & complexity: Solo freelancer vs. 200-person org have radically
different density needs.
Phase 2 — Aesthetic Direction
Commit to a bold, specific aesthetic direction before writing a single line.
PM tools are functional, but function without form is forgettable. Pick a
direction and execute it with conviction:

PM-Specific Aesthetic Archetypes
Use these as springboards, not templates. Twist them. Combine unexpectedly.

Direction	Vibe
War Room	High-contrast, dense, military-grid precision. For power users.
Studio	Editorial whitespace, serif type, gallery-like task display.
Terminal	Monospace everything, phosphor glow, CLI aesthetic with GUI power.
Blueprint	Technical drafting, grid lines, annotation-style labels, ink-on-paper
Dossier	Classified document energy, redaction aesthetics, archival type.
Control Room	Ambient dark UI, glowing indicators, mission-critical density.
Field Notes	Handwritten texture, paper grain, tactile and humanist.
Ledger	Accounting heritage, ruled lines, tabular clarity, serif numbers.
Cartography	Spatial, map-like hierarchy, territory and region metaphors.
Brutalist PM	Raw structure exposed, unstyled-ish but deliberate, anti-corporate.
Never default to: rounded cards on white/gray backgrounds, blue primary
buttons, Inter or Space Grotesk, purple gradient hero sections, or any layout
that could appear in a SaaS template marketplace.

Typography Rules
Choose a display/heading font that carries personality: condensed
grotesques, slab serifs, geometric serifs, wide-tracking caps, or monospace
can all work depending on direction.
Pair with a data/body font optimized for dense information: tabular
figures, legibility at small sizes, clear differentiation between characters
(1, l, I; 0, O).
Use type scale intentionally: PM tools often need 5–7 levels of hierarchy
(page title → section → task title → metadata → label → timestamp →
placeholder). Define all of them.
Avoid: Inter, Roboto, Arial, system-ui as primary choices. These are
acceptable as data fonts only if the display font carries the identity.
Color & Theme
Commit to a dominant palette with 1–2 sharp accent colors. PM tools live
in grayscale; the accent must work hard.
Define semantic color rigorously: status colors (todo, in progress,
blocked, done, cancelled) must be distinct, accessible, and on-brand.
Use CSS custom properties for every token: colors, spacing, radii,
shadows, transitions.
Consider information-layer coloring: use color to encode data (priority,
assignee, project) rather than just decoration.
Light and dark themes should be considered from the start, even if only one
is implemented. PM tools are used at 11pm.
Motion & Interaction
Task state changes deserve micro-animation: completing a task, moving a
card, collapsing a section.
Data loading should feel intentional: skeleton states, progressive
disclosure, not spinners.
Drag interactions (if kanban/list): visual feedback on drag start, drop
target highlighting, satisfying snap-to-place.
Dense views: staggered load animations only if performance allows. Never
animate what users will interact with 200 times/day — animation fatigue is
real in PM tools.
High-impact moments: project creation, milestone completion, sprint close
— these deserve ceremony.
Use CSS animations for static components. Use Motion (Framer Motion) for
React when interaction state is involved.
Spatial Composition
Density is a design choice, not a default. Know whether this view should
be breathable or packed.
PM interfaces often need multi-pane layouts: sidebar + main + detail
panel. Handle this intentionally.
Hierarchy through space: the most important action on the screen should
command the most visual weight and position.
Grid discipline: establish a clear grid (4pt or 8pt base unit) and
maintain it. PM tool messiness comes from inconsistent spacing.
Consider progressive disclosure: don't show all metadata at once. Surface
on hover, expand on click, reveal on need.
Visual Details & Atmosphere
Empty states are a design moment, not an afterthought. PM tools live in
empty states.
Status indicators: custom, on-brand. Not Bootstrap badges. Not Tailwind
defaults.
Data visualization: progress rings, burndown micro-charts, workload
bars — even tiny inline sparklines should match the aesthetic.
Backgrounds: avoid flat white/gray. Subtle grid, ruled lines, paper
texture, or gradient depth all work depending on direction.
Borders and dividers: use deliberately. A single well-placed rule can do
more than a card shadow.
Phase 3 — PM Component Patterns
When building specific component types, follow these quality standards:

Task / Issue Row
Must display: title, status, assignee, priority, due date — without feeling
cluttered.
Status must be scannable at a glance (icon + color, not text alone).
Hover state must reveal secondary actions without layout shift.
Consider: inline editing, keyboard navigation, bulk selection.
Kanban Board
Column headers must communicate WIP limit, count, and status clearly.
Cards must balance information density with drag usability.
Column overflow behavior must be designed (scroll vs. collapse).
Empty columns need character, not just a dashed border.
Timeline / Gantt
Date axis must handle variable zoom (day/week/month/quarter).
Bar overlaps and dependencies must be legible.
Today indicator must be obvious without being garish.
"Now" context (what's overdue, what's this week) must be immediately clear.
Dashboard / Overview
Every metric must answer a question a real user asks.
Avoid vanity metrics (total tasks created since forever).
Prioritize: what needs attention NOW, what's at risk, what's on track.
Charts must use the design system palette, not default chart library colors.
Sidebar / Navigation
Active state must be unmistakable.
Project list with status indicators (health, unread, overdue) at a glance.
Collapse behavior must be smooth and preserve context.
Keyboard shortcuts should be discoverable.
Forms (Task Creation, Project Setup)
Minimize required fields. Progressive disclosure for advanced options.
Smart defaults based on context.
Validation must be helpful, not punitive.
Submission must feel satisfying — this is a workflow moment.
Phase 4 — Implementation Standards
Code Quality
Production-grade: no placeholder logic, no TODO comments left in delivered
code, no console.log debris.
Semantic HTML: use <time>, <progress>, <details>, <dialog> where
appropriate. Screen readers exist.
Accessibility: keyboard navigation, ARIA labels on icon-only buttons, focus
rings that match the design system (not the browser default).
Responsive: define breakpoints appropriate to PM tools (mobile is real;
tablets exist; wide monitors are common).
CSS Architecture
CSS custom properties for all design tokens.
BEM, CSS Modules, or Tailwind — pick one, use it consistently.
No magic numbers. Every value should be derivable from the token system.
Avoid !important. If you need it, the architecture is wrong.
State & Data
Use realistic mock data that reflects actual PM tool complexity: multiple
projects, varied statuses, realistic names, real-feeling dates.
Handle loading, empty, error, and populated states for every data-dependent
component.
If React: prefer controlled components, clear prop interfaces, typed if
possible (TypeScript preferred).
Performance Considerations
PM tools are used all day. Heavy animations on frequently-used components
will cause fatigue and CPU drain. Restrain motion on repeated interactions.
Virtualize long lists if the component implies unbounded data (task lists,
activity feeds).
Lazy-load heavy panels (detail views, reports).
Output Format
Deliver:

A brief design rationale (3–5 sentences): aesthetic direction chosen,
why it fits the PM context, what makes it distinctive.
Working implementation code: complete, runnable, properly formatted.
Usage notes (if needed): how to extend, what props/data it expects, any
dependencies required.
Do not deliver:

Partial components with "you can add X here" gaps.
Generic styling that could apply to any SaaS product.
Inaccessible icon-only interfaces with no labels.
Dashboard widgets that show fake data without acknowledging it's mock data.
The Standard
The test: would a design-literate PM or engineering lead look at this and say
"who made this?" — not because it's bizarre, but because it has a point of
view? PM tools don't have to be boring. The best ones aren't.

Every component should feel like it was designed for a specific team, with a
specific culture, solving a specific problem. Generic is the enemy.

